The picture is not indeed wholly without its other side, when the candour of the historiari asserts itself against the desire to idealize. Itis admitted that their independence is even excessive ¹, that they ⁶ are torn to pieces by internal feuds¹, impulsive and unsteady in battle ³, indolent and quarrelsome in peace ⁴, predatory⁵, drunlren¹¹‚ ⁸ absorbed by the passion for gambling⁷; in fact that their finer qualities are by no means without thevices which in a low state of civilization are apt to go with them.

In attempting to gather the description of the country and its people into generalizations, we are often baffled by difficulties probably due to unexplained diversity. The discrepancies between Caesar and Tacitus, or those between Tacitus and himself, or between either of them and the earliest later knowledge, may often arise from the different stages of civilization of different tribes and from the attempt
